# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: annual-review-of-genetics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/abstracting-and-indexing] An **abstracting service** is a service that provides abstracts of publications, often on a subject or group of related subjects, usually on a subscription basis.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/abstracting-and-indexing] An **indexing service** is a service that assigns descriptors and other kinds of access points to documents.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/abstracting-and-indexing] The word indexing service is today mostly used for computer programs, but may also cover services providing back-of-the-book indexes, journal indexes, and related kinds of indexes.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/abstracting-and-indexing] An **indexing and abstracting service** is a service that provides shortening or summarizing of documents and assigning of descriptors for referencing documents.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/abstracting-and-indexing] The product is often an **abstracts journal** or a bibliographic index, which may be a subject bibliography or a bibliographic database.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/abstracting-and-indexing] Guidelines for indexing and abstracting, including the evaluation of such services, are given in the literature of library and information science.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/academic-search] Academic Search Complete was first published in 2007 as Academic Premier.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/academic-search] It is an indexing and abstracting service, accessible via the World Wide Web.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/academic-search] Coverage includes more than 8,500 full-text periodicals, including more than 7,300 peer-reviewed journals.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/academic-search] In addition to full text, A. cademic Complete offers indexing and abstracts for more than 10,100 journals and a total of more than 10,600 publications including monographs, reports, conference proceedings, among others.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/academic-search] Although coverage is from 1965 to the present, PDF back-file content coverage is from 1887.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/academic-search] Field searches include full text articles (references can be included), academic journal titles, author, publication dates, abstracts, summations, cited references, and relevant images.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/academic-search] Article results can also include thumbnail images.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] Campbell earned his bachelor's degree at the University of California, Berkeley (1950) and master's (1951) and doctoral (1953) degrees from the University of Illinois where he worked with Sol Spiegelman.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] From 1953-1957 Campbell was on the faculty of the University of Michigan.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] During the summers he spent time with Gio ("Joe") Bertani at Caltech and the University of Southern California, at Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory and at the Institut Pasteur with François Jacob.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] In 1958 he married Alice del Campillo, a Ph.D. student in biochemistry at the University of Michigan.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] They spent the year after their marriage working in Paris.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] The two worked closely together throughout their careers, investigating research questions such as the encoding of heat-sensitive endolysin and the biosynthesis and regulation of biotin.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] Campbell spent the next nine years on the faculty of the University of Rochester, where he made significant discoveries about lambda phage.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] In 1968 Campbell joined the Department of Biology at Stanford University, where he led his own laboratory.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] He was appointed to the Barbara Kimball Browning endowed chair in 1992.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] Campbell was the editor of the *Annual Review of Genetics* from 1985 to 2012.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] Campbell's research has concentrated on the genetics of bacteria and their viruses, especially the integration of viral DNA into host chromosomes.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] His most prominent discovery was the proposal of the "Campbell model" of virus insertion, where viral DNA is inserted into the host chromosome, becoming covalently bonded to the bacterial DNA, and then remains dormant until activation.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] Campbell's research was focused on a specific bacterial virus, phage lambda, and its host bacterium *E. coli*, but the model provided insights into how extrachromosomal DNA can be inserted and excised in other organisms.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] This model was proposed in the book *Episomes* published in 1968, the first comprehensive treatment of plasmid biology.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] It was described as "a wide-ranging and critical evaluation of the experimental foundation of the episome concept".
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] Early studies on bacterial viruses began after the discovery by Twort and d'Herelle of 'filterable agents' which were able to destroy bacteria.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] These were demonstrated by creating a lawn of bacteria on appropriate media, mixing with these 'filterable agents' and then observing areas of destroyed cells seen as cleared circular areas (plaques) on the lawn.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] These plaques were interpreted as the result of a single agent infecting a bacterial cell, reproducing in the cell and then bursting open to infect surrounding cells, repeating the process until a clear circular area of destroyed cells becomes visible to the unaided eye.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] These filterable agents were named bacteriophages (eaters of bacteria) or phage for short.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] The 1940s produced the first pictures of bacterial viruses using electron microscopy produced the first photos of bacterial viruses, and research on the mechanism of infection and reproduction dramatically increased.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] One of the focal points of this research was Cold Spring Harbor Laboratory on Long Island, where a 'phage group' led by Salvador Luria, Max Delbrück, Alfred Hershey and others met in the summers for research and training of new investigators.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] In 1951 Esther Lederberg discovered lambda phage, which had an unusual characteristic.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] While lambda could infect and reproduce in some strains of its host bacterium E. coli, other strains seemed immune to infection.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] However, when the immune strains were mixed with non-immune strains, occasionally lambda phage could be observed infecting the non-immune strains.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] Further research suggested that the immune strains contained a dormant copy of the lambda genome which protected it from infection, but that dormant copy could be activated into the active viral state to begin a new round of infection.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] This dormant phase was called the 'lysogenic' state and the actively infectious state was called the 'lytic' state.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] The dormant form of the lambda genome was called the 'prophage'.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] Study of phage lambda over the next 50 years provided valuable insights into virus life cycles, the regulation and expression of genetic material, and the mechanism of integration and excision of genetic material into chromosomal locations.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] Allan Campbell's contribution to the field with the 'Campbell model' of integration and excision marked a major step forward in the understanding of this process.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] Campbell was an elected member of the National Academy of Sciences (1971), the American Academy of Arts and Sciences (1971), the American Association for the Advancement of Science (1983) and a fellow of the American Academy of Microbiology.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] Campbell received the 2004 Abbott-ASM Lifetime Achievement Award from the American Society for Microbiology at the society's 104th general meeting in New Orleans on Monday, May 24, 2004.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] Campbell delivered the Abbott-ASM Award Lecture and was honored at a dinner ceremony that evening.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/allan-m-campbell] The award includes a $20,000 cash prize and a commemorative piece.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/andrew-g-clark] Clark received a Bachelor of Science from Brown University in 1976, followed by a Ph.D. in population genetics from Stanford University in 1980.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/andrew-g-clark] He then worked as a postdoctoral researcher at Arizona State University and the University of Aarhus, before joining the faculty of Penn State University's Department of Biology.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/andrew-g-clark] Since 2002, he has been a professor at Cornell University.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/andrew-g-clark] He was elected a fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science in 1994, and a member of the National Academy of Sciences in 2012.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/andrew-g-clark] Clark's laboratory group researches genetic variation and adaptation using both human data and the laboratory model *Drosophila melanogaster*.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The animal kingdom is divided into five major clades, namely Porifera, Ctenophora, Placozoa, Cnidaria and Bilateria.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The much smaller basal phylum Xenacoelomorpha have an uncertain position within Bilateria.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals first appeared in the fossil record in the late Cryogenian period and diversified in the subsequent Ediacaran period in what is known as the Avalon explosion.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Nearly all modern animal phyla first appeared in the fossil record as marine species during the Cambrian explosion, which began around 539 million years ago (Mya), and most classes during the Ordovician radiation 485.4 Mya.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Common to all living animals, 6,331 groups of genes have been identified that may have arisen from a single common ancestor that lived about 650 Mya during the Cryogenian period.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Historically, Aristotle divided animals into those with blood and those without.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical biological classification for animals in 1758 with his *Systema Naturae*, which Jean-Baptiste Lamarck expanded into 14 phyla by 1809.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into the multicellular **Metazoa** (now synonymous with Animalia) and the Protozoa, single-celled organisms no longer considered animals.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In modern times, the biological classification of animals relies on advanced techniques, such as molecular phylogenetics, which are effective at demonstrating the evolutionary relationships between taxa.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Humans make use of many other animal species for food (including meat, eggs, and dairy products), for materials (such as leather, fur, and wool), as pets and as working animals for transportation, and services.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Dogs, the first domesticated animal, have been used in hunting, in security and in warfare, as have horses, pigeons and birds of prey; while other terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sports, trophies or profits.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Non-human animals are also an important cultural element of human evolution, having appeared in cave arts and totems since the earliest times, and are frequently featured in mythology, religion, arts, literature, heraldry, politics, and sports.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The word *animal* comes from the Latin noun *animal* of the same meaning, which is itself derived from Latin *animalis* 'having breath or soul'.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The biological definition includes all members of the kingdom Animalia.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In colloquial usage, the term *animal* is often used to refer only to nonhuman animals.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The term *metazoa* is derived from Ancient Greek μετα *meta* 'after' (in biology, the prefix *meta-* stands for 'later') and ζῷᾰ *zōia* 'animals', plural of ζῷον *zōion* 'animal'.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] A **metazoan** is any member of the group *Metazoa*.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals have several characteristics that they share with other living things.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals are eukaryotic, multicellular, and aerobic, as are plants and fungi.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Unlike plants and algae, which produce their own food, animals cannot produce their own food, a feature they share with fungi.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals ingest organic material and digest it internally.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Typically, there is an internal digestive chamber with either one opening (in Ctenophora, Cnidaria, and flatworms) or two openings (in most bilaterians).
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animal development is controlled by Hox genes, which signal the times and places to develop structures such as body segments and limbs.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] During development, the animal extracellular matrix forms a relatively flexible framework upon which cells can move about and be reorganised into specialised tissues and organs, making the formation of complex structures possible, and allowing cells to be differentiated.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The extracellular matrix may be calcified, forming structures such as shells, bones, and spicules.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In contrast, the cells of other multicellular organisms (primarily algae, plants, and fungi) are held in place by cell walls, and so develop by progressive growth.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Nearly all animals make use of some form of sexual reproduction.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] They produce haploid gametes by meiosis; the smaller, motile gametes are spermatozoa and the larger, non-motile gametes are ova.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] These fuse to form zygotes, which develop via mitosis into a hollow sphere, called a blastula.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In sponges, blastula larvae swim to a new location, attach to the seabed, and develop into a new sponge.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In most other groups, the blastula undergoes more complicated rearrangement.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] It first invaginates to form a gastrula with a digestive chamber and two separate germ layers, an external ectoderm and an internal endoderm.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In most cases, a third germ layer, the mesoderm, also develops between them.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] These germ layers then differentiate to form tissues and organs.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Repeated instances of mating with a close relative during sexual reproduction generally leads to inbreeding depression within a population due to the increased prevalence of harmful recessive traits.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals have evolved numerous mechanisms for avoiding close inbreeding.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Some animals are capable of asexual reproduction, which often results in a genetic clone of the parent.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] This may take place through fragmentation; budding, such as in *Hydra* and other cnidarians; or parthenogenesis, where fertile eggs are produced without mating, such as in aphids.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals are categorised into ecological groups depending on their trophic levels and how they consume organic material.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Such groupings include carnivores (further divided into subcategories such as piscivores, insectivores, ovivores, etc.), herbivores (subcategorised into folivores, graminivores, frugivores, granivores, nectarivores, algivores, etc.), omnivores, fungivores, scavengers/detritivores, and parasites.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Interactions between animals of each biome form complex food webs within that ecosystem.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In carnivorous or omnivorous species, predation is a consumer–resource interaction where the predator feeds on another organism, its prey, who often evolves anti-predator adaptations to avoid being fed upon.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Selective pressures imposed on one another lead to an evolutionary arms race between predator and prey, resulting in various antagonistic/competitive coevolutions.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Almost all multicellular predators are animals.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Some consumers use multiple methods; for example, in parasitoid wasps, the larvae feed on the hosts' living tissues, killing them in the process, but the adults primarily consume nectar from flowers.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Other animals may have very specific feeding behaviours, such as hawksbill sea turtles which mainly eat sponges.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Most animals rely on biomass and bioenergy produced by plants and phytoplanktons (collectively called producers) through photosynthesis.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Herbivores, as primary consumers, eat the plant material directly to digest and absorb the nutrients, while carnivores and other animals on higher trophic levels indirectly acquire the nutrients by eating the herbivores or other animals that have eaten the herbivores.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals oxidise carbohydrates, lipids, proteins and other biomolecules in cellular respiration, which allows the animal to grow and to sustain basal metabolism and fuel other biological processes such as locomotion.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Some benthic animals living close to hydrothermal vents and cold seeps on the dark sea floor consume organic matter produced through chemosynthesis (via oxidising inorganic compounds such as hydrogen sulfide) by archaea and bacteria.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals originated in the ocean; all extant animal phyla, except for Micrognathozoa and Onychophora, feature at least some marine species.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] However, several lineages of arthropods begun to colonise land around the same time as land plants, between 510 and 471 million years ago, during the Late Cambrian or Early Ordovician periods.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Vertebrates such as the lobe-finned fish *Tiktaalik* started to move on to land in the late Devonian, about 375 million years ago.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Other notable animal groups that colonized land environments are Mollusca, Platyhelmintha, Annelida, Tardigrada, Onychophora, Rotifera, Nematoda.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals occupy virtually all of earth's habitats and microhabitats, with faunas adapted to salt water, hydrothermal vents, fresh water, hot springs, swamps, forests, pastures, deserts, air, and the interiors of other organisms.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals are however not particularly heat tolerant; very few of them can survive at constant temperatures above 50 °C (122 °F) or in the most extreme cold deserts of continental Antarctica.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The collective global geomorphic influence of animals on the processes shaping the Earth's surface remains largely understudied, with most studies limited to individual species and well-known exemplars.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The blue whale (*Balaenoptera musculus*) is the largest animal that has ever lived, weighing up to 190 tonnes and measuring up to 33.6 metres (110 ft) long.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The largest extant terrestrial animal is the African bush elephant (*Loxodonta africana*), weighing up to 12.25 tonnes and measuring up to 10.67 metres (35.0 ft) long.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The largest terrestrial animals that ever lived were titanosaur sauropod dinosaurs such as *Argentinosaurus*, which may have weighed as much as 73 tonnes, and *Supersaurus* which may have reached 39 metres.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Several animals are microscopic; some Myxozoa (obligate parasites within the Cnidaria) never grow larger than 20 μm, and one of the smallest species (*Myxobolus shekel*) is no more than 8.5 μm when fully grown.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The following table lists estimated numbers of described extant species for the major animal phyla, along with their principal habitats (terrestrial, fresh water, and marine), and free-living or parasitic ways of life.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Species estimates shown here are based on numbers described scientifically; much larger estimates have been calculated based on various means of prediction, and these can vary wildly.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] For instance, around 25,000–27,000 species of nematodes have been described, while published estimates of the total number of nematode species include 10,000–20,000; 500,000; 10 million; and 100 million.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Using patterns within the taxonomic hierarchy, the total number of animal species—including those not yet described—was calculated to be about 7.77 million in 2011.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Evidence of animals is found as long ago as the Cryogenian period.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] 24-Isopropylcholestane (24-ipc) has been found in rocks from roughly 650 million years ago; it is only produced by sponges and pelagophyte algae.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Its likely origin is from sponges based on molecular clock estimates for the origin of 24-ipc production in both groups.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Analyses of pelagophyte algae consistently recover a Phanerozoic origin, while analyses of sponges recover a Neoproterozoic origin, consistent with the appearance of 24-ipc in the fossil record.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The first body fossils of animals appear in the Ediacaran, represented by forms such as *Charnia* and *Spriggina*.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] It had long been doubted whether these fossils truly represented animals, but the discovery of the animal lipid cholesterol in fossils of *Dickinsonia* establishes their nature.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals are thought to have originated under low-oxygen conditions, suggesting that they were capable of living entirely by anaerobic respiration, but as they became specialised for aerobic metabolism they became fully dependent on oxygen in their environments.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Many animal phyla first appear in the fossil record during the Cambrian explosion, starting about 539 million years ago, in beds such as the Burgess Shale.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Extant phyla in these rocks include molluscs, brachiopods, onychophorans, tardigrades, arthropods, echinoderms and hemichordates, along with numerous now-extinct forms such as the predatory *Anomalocaris*.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The apparent suddenness of the event may however be an artefact of the fossil record, rather than showing that all these animals appeared simultaneously.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] That view is supported by the discovery of *Auroralumina attenboroughii*, the earliest known Ediacaran crown-group cnidarian (557–562 mya, some 20 million years before the Cambrian explosion) from Charnwood Forest, England.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] It is thought to be one of the earliest predators, catching small prey with its nematocysts as modern cnidarians do.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Some palaeontologists have suggested that animals appeared much earlier than the Cambrian explosion, possibly as early as 1 billion years ago.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Early fossils that might represent animals appear for example in the 665-million-year-old rocks of the Trezona Formation of South Australia.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] These fossils are interpreted as most probably being early sponges.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Trace fossils such as tracks and burrows found in the Tonian period (from 1 gya) may indicate the presence of triploblastic worm-like animals, roughly as large (about 5 mm wide) and complex as earthworms.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] However, similar tracks are produced by the giant single-celled protist *Gromia sphaerica*, so the Tonian trace fossils may not indicate early animal evolution.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Around the same time, the layered mats of microorganisms called stromatolites decreased in diversity, perhaps due to grazing by newly evolved animals.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Objects such as sediment-filled tubes that resemble trace fossils of the burrows of wormlike animals have been found in 1.2 gya rocks in North America, in 1.5 gya rocks in Australia and North America, and in 1.7 gya rocks in Australia.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Their interpretation as having an animal origin is disputed, as they might be water-escape or other structures.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals are monophyletic, meaning they are derived from a common ancestor.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals are the sister group to the choanoflagellates, with which they form the Choanozoa.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Ros-Rocher and colleagues (2021) trace the origins of animals to unicellular ancestors, providing the external phylogeny shown in the cladogram.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Uncertainty of relationships is indicated with dashed lines.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The animal clade had certainly originated by 650 mya, and may have come into being as much as 800 mya, based on molecular clock evidence for different phyla.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The relationships at the base of the animal tree have been debated.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Other than Ctenophora, the Bilateria and Cnidaria are the only groups with symmetry, and other evidence shows they are closely related.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In addition to sponges, Placozoa has no symmetry and was often considered a "missing link" between protists and multicellular animals.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The presence of hox genes in Placozoa shows that they were once more complex.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The Porifera (sponges) have long been assumed to be sister to the rest of the animals, but there is evidence that the Ctenophora may be in that position.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Molecular phylogenetics has supported both the sponge-sister and ctenophore-sister hypotheses.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Sponges are physically very distinct from other animals, and were long thought to have diverged first, representing the oldest animal phylum and forming a sister clade to all other animals.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Despite their morphological dissimilarity with all other animals, genetic evidence suggests sponges may be more closely related to other animals than the comb jellies are.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Sponges lack the complex organisation found in most other animal phyla; their cells are differentiated, but in most cases not organised into distinct tissues, unlike all other animals.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Sponges are almost entirely sessile in their adult stage.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Sponges lack a digestive, circulatory, respiratory, or excretory system.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Instead, they rely on the flow of water through their bodies to perform these functions.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Many have adapted a hollow structure to facilitate the flow of water through their bodies.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] They typically feed by drawing in water through pores, filtering out small particles of food.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] They absorb oxygen dissolved in water, and they release carbon dioxide and nitrogenous waste into water that flows through them.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Sponges can reproduce sexually and asexually.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Asexual reproduction happens through a variety of mechanisms including by fragmentation, where a piece of the sponge splits off and reestablishes somewhere else.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] For sexual reproduction, most sponges are hermaphrodites, they produce both egg and sperm cells.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Comb jellies, members of Ctenophora, are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Ctenophora have distinct tissues, but these are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] They move using large arrays of cilia, called swimming plates.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] They have are unique in having colloblasts, structures on their tentacles that help them catch prey.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] They have nerve cells, but lack a brain or central nervous system.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Instead their nerves are arranged into a nerve net.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Their nerves are very different from those of other animals, and evidence suggests that their nerves developed independently of the nerves of other animals.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Like Ctenophora, Cnidaria are radially symmetric and have digestive chambers with a single opening, which serves as both mouth and anus.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] They also have distinct tissues that are not organised into discrete organs.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Members of the group Anthozoa, such as sea anemones, coral, and sea pens only are sessile polyps.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Most members of Medusozoa, including jellyfish and most hydrozoans, have a polyp form as well, but also have a motile medusae stage.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The medusae stage are commonly known as jellyfish.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Cnidaria are diploblastic, having only two main germ layers, ectoderm and endoderm.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The tiny placozoans have no permanent digestive chamber and no symmetry; they superficially resemble amoebae.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Their phylogeny is poorly defined, and under active research.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The remaining animals, the great majority—comprising some 29 phyla and over a million species—form the Bilateria clade, which have a bilaterally symmetric body plan.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The Bilateria are triploblastic, with three well-developed germ layers, and their tissues form distinct organs.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The digestive chamber has two openings, a mouth and an anus, and in the Nephrozoa there is an internal body cavity, a coelom or pseudocoelom.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] These animals have a head end (anterior) and a tail end (posterior), a back (dorsal) surface and a belly (ventral) surface, and a left and a right side.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] A modern consensus phylogenetic tree for the Bilateria is shown below.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Having a front end means that this part of the body encounters stimuli, such as food, favouring cephalisation, the development of a head with sense organs and a mouth.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Many bilaterians have a combination of circular muscles that constrict the body, making it longer, and an opposing set of longitudinal muscles, that shorten the body; these enable soft-bodied animals with a hydrostatic skeleton to move by peristalsis.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] They also have a gut that extends through the basically cylindrical body from mouth to anus.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Many bilaterian phyla have primary larvae which swim with cilia and have an apical organ containing sensory cells.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] However, over evolutionary time, descendant spaces have evolved which have lost one or more of each of these characteristics.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] For example, adult echinoderms are radially symmetric (unlike their larvae), while some parasitic worms have extremely simplified body structures.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Genetic studies have considerably changed zoologists' understanding of the relationships within the Bilateria.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Most appear to belong to two major lineages, the protostomes and the deuterostomes.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] It is often suggested that the basalmost bilaterians are the Xenacoelomorpha, with all other bilaterians belonging to the subclade Nephrozoa.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] However, this suggestion has been contested, with other studies finding that xenacoelomorphs are more closely related to Ambulacraria than to other bilaterians.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Protostomes and deuterostomes differ in several ways.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Early in development, deuterostome embryos undergo radial cleavage during cell division, while many protostomes (the Spiralia) undergo spiral cleavage.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals from both groups possess a complete digestive tract, but in protostomes the first opening of the embryonic gut develops into the mouth, and the anus forms secondarily.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In deuterostomes, the anus forms first while the mouth develops secondarily.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Most protostomes have schizocoelous development, where cells simply fill in the interior of the gastrula to form the mesoderm.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In deuterostomes, the mesoderm forms by enterocoelic pouching, through invagination of the endoderm.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The main deuterostome taxa are the Ambulacraria and the Chordata.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Ambulacraria are exclusively marine and include acorn worms, starfish, sea urchins, and sea cucumbers.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The chordates are dominated by the vertebrates (animals with backbones), which consist of fishes, amphibians, reptiles, birds, and mammals.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The protostomes include the Ecdysozoa, named after their shared trait of ecdysis, growth by moulting, Among the largest ecdysozoan phyla are the arthropods and the nematodes.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The rest of the protostomes are in the Spiralia, named for their pattern of developing by spiral cleavage in the early embryo.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Major spiralian phyla include the annelids and molluscs.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In the classical era, Aristotle divided animals, based on his own observations, into those with blood (roughly, the vertebrates) and those without.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In 1758, Carl Linnaeus created the first hierarchical classification in his *Systema Naturae*.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In his original scheme, the animals were one of three kingdoms, divided into the classes of Vermes, Insecta, Pisces, Amphibia, Aves, and Mammalia.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Since then, the last four have all been subsumed into a single phylum, the Chordata, while his Insecta (which included the crustaceans and arachnids) and Vermes have been renamed or broken up.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The process was begun in 1793 by Jean-Baptiste de Lamarck, who called the Vermes *une espèce de chaos* ('a chaotic mess') and split the group into three new phyla: worms, echinoderms, and polyps (which contained corals and jellyfish).
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] By 1809, in his *Philosophie Zoologique*, Lamarck had created nine phyla apart from vertebrates (where he still had four phyla: mammals, birds, reptiles, and fish) and molluscs, namely cirripedes, annelids, crustaceans, arachnids, insects, worms, radiates, polyps, and infusorians.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] This division into four was followed by the embryologist Karl Ernst von Baer in 1828, the zoologist Louis Agassiz in 1857, and the comparative anatomist Richard Owen in 1860.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In 1874, Ernst Haeckel divided the animal kingdom into two subkingdoms: Metazoa (multicellular animals, with five phyla: coelenterates, echinoderms, articulates, molluscs, and vertebrates) and Protozoa (single-celled animals), including a sixth animal phylum, sponges.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The protozoa were later moved to the former kingdom Protista, leaving only the Metazoa as a synonym of Animalia.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The human population exploits a large number of other animal species for food, both of domesticated livestock species in animal husbandry and, mainly at sea, by hunting wild species.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Marine fish of many species are caught commercially for food.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] A smaller number of species are farmed commercially.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Humans and their livestock make up more than 90% of the biomass of all terrestrial vertebrates, and almost as much as all insects combined.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Invertebrates including cephalopods, crustaceans, insects—principally bees and silkworms—and bivalve or gastropod molluscs are hunted or farmed for food, fibres.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Chickens, cattle, sheep, pigs, and other animals are raised as livestock for meat across the world.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animal fibres such as wool and silk are used to make textiles, while animal sinews have been used as lashings and bindings, and leather is widely used to make shoes and other items.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals have been hunted and farmed for their fur to make items such as coats and hats.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Dyestuffs including carmine (cochineal), shellac, and kermes have been made from the bodies of insects.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Working animals including cattle and horses have been used for work and transport from the first days of agriculture.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals such as the fruit fly *Drosophila melanogaster* serve a major role in science as experimental models.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals have been used to create vaccines since their discovery in the 18th century.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Some medicines such as the cancer drug trabectedin are based on toxins or other molecules of animal origin.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] People have used hunting dogs to help chase down and retrieve animals, and birds of prey to catch birds and mammals, while tethered cormorants have been used to catch fish.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Poison dart frogs have been used to poison the tips of blowpipe darts.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] A wide variety of animals are kept as pets, from invertebrates such as tarantulas, octopuses, and praying mantises, reptiles such as snakes and chameleons, and birds including canaries, parakeets, and parrots all finding a place.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] However, the most kept pet species are mammals, namely dogs, cats, and rabbits.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] There is a tension between the role of animals as companions to humans, and their existence as individuals with rights of their own.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] A wide variety of terrestrial and aquatic animals are hunted for sport.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The signs of the Western and Chinese zodiacs are based on animals.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] In China and Japan, the butterfly has been seen as the personification of a person's soul, and in classical representation the butterfly is also the symbol of the soul.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals have been the subjects of art from the earliest times, both historical, as in ancient Egypt, and prehistoric, as in the cave paintings at Lascaux.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Major animal paintings include Albrecht Dürer's 1515 *The Rhinoceros*, and George Stubbs's c.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Insects, birds and mammals play roles in literature and film, such as in giant bug movies.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Animals including insects and mammals feature in mythology and religion.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] The scarab beetle was sacred in ancient Egypt, and the cow is sacred in Hinduism.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/animal] Among other mammals, deer, horses, lions, bats, bears, and wolves are the subjects of myths and worship.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] The ***Annual Review of Analytical Chemistry*** is a peer-reviewed academic journal that publishes an annual volume of review articles relevant to analytical chemistry.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] It was established in 2008 and is published by Annual Reviews.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] As of 2023, it is being published as open access, under the Subscribe to Open model.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] The *Annual Review of Analytical Chemistry* was first published in 2008 by nonprofit publisher Annual Reviews.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] Though it began with a physical edition, it is now only published electronically.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] The *Annual Review of Analytical Chemistry* defines its scope as covering significant developments in analytical chemistry, drawing from the related disciplines of biology, engineering, and physics.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] As of 2025, *Journal Citation Reports* lists the journal's impact factor as 7.5, ranking it eighth of 111 journals in the category "Chemistry, Analytical" and second of 44 in "Spectroscopy".
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] It is abstracted and indexed in Scopus, Science Citation Index Expanded, EMBASE, MEDLINE, and Academic Search, among others.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] The *Annual Review of Analytical Chemistry* is helmed by the editor or the co-editors.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] The editor is assisted by the editorial committee, which includes associate editors, regular members, and occasionally guest editors.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] Guest members participate at the invitation of the editor, and serve terms of one year.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] All other members of the editorial committee are appointed by the Annual Reviews board of directors and serve five-year terms.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] The editorial committee determines which topics should be included in each volume and solicits reviews from qualified authors.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] Unsolicited manuscripts are not accepted.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] Peer review of accepted manuscripts is undertaken by the editorial committee.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] Dates indicate publication years in which someone was credited as a lead editor or co-editor of a journal volume.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] The planning process for a volume begins well before the volume appears, so appointment to the position of lead editor generally occurred prior to the first year shown here.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] An editor who has retired or died may be credited as a lead editor of a volume that they helped to plan, even if it is published after their retirement or death.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-analytical-chemistry] Previous members (as of 2022) were: Patrick R.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] The ***Annual Review of Animal Biosciences*** is a peer-reviewed scientific journal published by Annual Reviews.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] It releases an annual volume of review articles relevant to the fields of zoology, veterinary medicine, animal husbandry, and conservation biology.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] As of 2023, *Annual Review of Animal Biosciences* is being published as open access, under the Subscribe to Open model.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] As of 2025, *Journal Citation Reports* lists the journal's impact factor for 2024 as 8.7.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] It was rated number one of 181 titles in Zoology, number one of 86 in "Agriculture, Dairy, and Animal Sciences", number one of 170 in "Veterinary Science" and number thirteen of 177 titles in Biotechnology and Applied Microbiology.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] The *Annual Review of Animal Biosciences* was first published in 2013, with Harris A.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] Michael Roberts as the founding co-editors.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] Though it was initially published in print, as of 2021 it is only published electronically.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] The *Annual Review of Animal Biosciences* defines its scope as covering significant developments relevant to biotechnology, genomics, genetics, veterinary medicine, animal breeding, and conservation biology.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] The intended audience for the journal is scientists and veterinarians involved with wild and domestic animals.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-animal-biosciences] It is abstracted and indexed in Scopus, Science Citation Index Expanded, MEDLINE, and Embase, among others.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-genetics] The ***Annual Review of Genetics*** is an annual peer-reviewed scientific review journal published by Annual Reviews.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-genetics] It was established in 1967 and covers all topics related to the genetics of viruses, bacteria, fungi, plants, and animals, including humans.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-genetics] The current editor is Tatjana Piotrowski.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-genetics] As of 2025, *Journal Citation Reports* gives the journal a 2024 impact factor of 8.6, ranking it tenth out of 191 journals in the category "Genetics & Heredity".
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-genetics] In 1965, the nonprofit publisher Annual Reviews surveyed geneticists to determine if there was a need for an annual journal that published review articles about recent developments in the field of genetics.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-genetics] Responses to the survey were favorable, with the first volume of the *Annual Review of Genetics* published two years later in 1967.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-genetics] As of 2020, it was published both in print and electronically.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-genetics] It defines its scope as covering various aspects of genetics, including molecular, cell, and developmental biology; behavioral genetics, population genetics, chromosome structure and transmission, gene function and expression, mutation and DNA repair, genomics, and immunogenetics.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-genetics] Various organisms are considered, including viruses, bacteria, fungi, plants, and animals.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-genetics] It is abstracted and indexed in Scopus, Science Citation Index Expanded, MEDLINE, Embase, and Academic Search, among others.
[src:annual-review-of-genetics/annual-review-of-genetics] The *Annual Review of Genetics* is helmed by the editor or the co-editors.
